The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Tuesday, January 20, 2004  The City Diary
																																																		The spate of accidents continued on city roads with Mondays toll being one. A 30-year-old cyclist, Kamal Bairagi, was run over by a school bus on Monday morning on Bangur Road on the northern fringes of the city. Police said Bairagi, a resident of Ultadanga, was rushed to RG Kar Hospital where he was pronounced brought dead. In another incident, a private bus on route 46A collided with a Matador van at Maniktala. The driver of the van sustained minor injuries. He was taken to RG Kar Medical College and Hospital, where he received medical attention and was released.																																																		Security measures for Republic Day are well underway in the city. Deputy commissioner of police, headquarters, H.P. Singh said on Monday that 13,000 police personnel will be deployed in two contingents in Calcutta. One contingent will be responsible for crowd control while the other will handle armed threats and sabotage.																																																		Trinamul Congress chief and union minister for coal and mines Mamata Banerjee unveiled the first-ever upgraded secondary school of the Calcutta Municipal Corporation (CMC), Nazrul Secondary School, on Monday at Badartala in Metiabruz. Speaking on the occasion, she said though the state government is responsible for education in West Bengal, the CMC would show the way in future. Two more primary schools under the CMC would soon be upgraded, the union minister said. Mayor Subrata Mukherjee, who was also present at the inaugural function, said there was no place for politics when it came to education and health-related issues.																																																		Sunil Chakraborty, a freedom-fighter and president of All India Bata Shop Employees, died on January 17 at a city nursing home. Chakraborty was born in Panchasar village in Dhaka, Bangladesh. At the age of 14, he took part in the freedom movement and later dedicated his life to the working class movement.																																																		A law-violation programme organised by the Joint Movement of School Teachers and Employees at Rani Rashmoni Avenue on Monday resulted in the arrest of 541 teachers, 37 of whom were women. Police took the agitators to Presidency jail in buses. The school teachers and employees were protesting the commercialisation and privatisation of education in the state. They were also demanding the implementation of the examination system from the primary level, timely provision of text books, uniforms and mid-day meals in schools. The list of demands included taking teachers on a permanent basis, not on contract.																																																		 Jet Airways on Monday launched a Calcutta-Agartala flight service by introducing the B 737-700 aircraft. Chief minister of Tripura Manik Sarkar received the first flight to the state capital. The flight will operate on Wednesday, Thursday and Friday and leave Calcutta at 5.05 pm. It will reach Agartala at 6 pm. The return flight to Calcutta will leave Agartala at 6.35 pm and reach Calcutta at 7.30 pm. The one-way economy class fare on the Calcutta-Agartala sector will be Rs 2,545 and business class Rs 3,695, airways officials said.																																																		The All India Minority Forum held a meeting on Sunday to protest the bandh called by Trinamul Congress on February 3 during Id-ud-joha and author Taslima Nasreens visit to Calcutta. Idris Ali, president of the organisation, said no political party should call a bandh during a religious festival. Ali also criticised the state government for allowing Nasreen to come to Calcutta and give her police protection even after her book Dwikhandito was banned.																																																		Akhil Bharat Vivekananda Yuva Mahamandal organised a rally at Sahid Minar on Sunday to pay homage to Swami Vivekananda on his birth anniversary.  TO Uttar Kolkata Manishi O Biplabi  Smriti Raksha Samity for organising a free health check-up  camp at Ahiritola
